**Loss Reserving** is the process of estimating the amount of money an insurer must set aside to pay for claims that have already occurred but have not yet been settled. It is a [[Retrospective Analysis]] that accounts for the "long tail" of insurance liabilities, ensuring the company's balance sheet accurately reflects its future obligations.

- The Total Loss Reserve is generally the sum of Case Reserves and IBNR:

> $$\text{Total Reserve} = \text{Case Reserves} + \text{IBNR}$$
>
> $$\text{IBNR} = \text{Incurred But Not Reported} + \text{Incurred But Not Enough Reported (IBNER)}$$

> [!example]- Estimating IBNR {Example}
> 
> An insurance company has a total of $10$ million in "Incurred Losses" (Paid + Case Reserves) for the 2025 accident year. Actuarial models suggest the "Ultimate Loss" will actually be $13$ million. What is the **IBNR** reserve required?
> 
> > [!answer]-
> > 
> > - **Estimated Ultimate Losses:** $13,000,000
> > - **Reported Incurred Losses:** $10,000,000
> > 
> > The **IBNR** (Incurred But Not Reported) is the "plug" figure representing the development still to come:
> > 
> > $$\text{IBNR} = \text{Ultimate} - \text{Incurred}$$
> > $$\text{IBNR} = 13,000,000 - 10,000,000 = \$3,000,000$$
> > 
> > > [!tip] Solvency Importance
> > > Underestimating reserves is a leading cause of insurance company insolvency. If the reserve is too low, the company's surplus (equity) is artificially inflated, hiding financial distress.
